In the French version attributed by Caxton to Christine de Pise the word is translated ‘⁴ rheume.’' Akyr, Eagre, Higre, or Agar, is a name to be traced probably to that of the great Ocean-god of the Northern Mythology, Oegir or AEgir; the drowned were the prey of Rr‘m, his consort. In Lyly's Galathea is the following allusion to the Akyr: “ He [Neptune] seudeth a monster called the Agar, against whose coming the waters roare, the fowles flie away, and the cattle of the field, for terror, shun the banks.'’ Finn Magnussen derives AEgir from the verb aegia, to fiow.
